{"translated_title": "Jordanian Company Provides Free Educational Content to Gaza Students", "translated_content": "Amman - After more than 8 months of efforts, the Jordanian company for e-learning solutions, Jo Academy, has officially managed to deliver free educational content to students in the Gaza Strip electronically. Educational content has been produced for all subjects in the Palestinian curriculum, in collaboration with a large number of Jordanian teachers, and with direct coordination between the Jordanian and Palestinian Ministries of Education. This initiative aims to empower over 650,000 male and female students in Gaza with educational material across all subjects, including science, mathematics, and both English and Arabic languages. This will facilitate the continuity of the educational process within the sector across all grades from the first grade to the 12th grade for those who have been deprived of education due to damage to infrastructure, including the destruction of educational centers, which has led to a complete halt of education in Gaza as a result of the ongoing war since October 7, 2023. According to the General Director of Jo Academy, Alaa Jarrar, the academy has provided the electronic content for free to students in Gaza as part of its community and national role, which is to harness technology to overcome the difficulties and challenges arising from emergency conditions, allowing Gazan students, in particular, to catch up on the current academic year, as well as students in the West Bank and occupied Jerusalem. He explained to Al Jazeera Net that the application is now available with its audio, visual, and written educational outputs, in addition to electronic exams that assess students' abilities and work to raise their educational level. Jarrar revealed that the number of downloads on the application for Gaza students has reached over 80,000, while the number of students who studied on it in recent weeks has reached 230,000, noting that one device is used by more than one student in a single family. Jo Academy signed a partnership and cooperation agreement yesterday, Thursday, with the Palestinian Ministry of Education, under which the mobile application available through the Wise School platform for teaching the Palestinian curriculum will be operated for free for the children of Palestine in Gaza, the West Bank, and occupied Jerusalem. The project aims, according to the academy director, to reach more than 650,000 male and female students in Gaza with electronic educational content. He pointed out that the application has been officially approved by the Palestinian Ministry of Education, allowing Gaza students to take exams at the end of the semester to obtain the educational certificate that qualifies them to advance to the next grade, according to the official and legal procedures followed. The Palestinian Minister of Education, Amjad Barham, confirmed that this platform will provide education for more than 600,000 Palestinian students studying in various school grades, and will enable the ministry to issue certificates for the grades that students have studied and been assessed through the application. The digital content provided by this initiative includes thousands of educational videos, explanations, and electronic tests via the application that can be downloaded on smart devices operating on both Android and iOS systems, allowing Palestinian students to study whether or not they have internet access, enabling them to continue their studies despite the challenges they face. For her part, the director of the free education platform project, Farah Aliyan, stated that the application comes to support the resilience of families in Gaza and Palestine in general, as it provides them with detailed explanations, worksheets, and exams without the need for the internet, and it has received full accreditation from the Palestinian Ministry of Education. She noted that the number of teachers and university professors who collaborated to complete the application reached 200 lecturers and more than 200 workers supervising its technical development. The application also provides some university specializations offered by the Jordanian Islamic Sciences University, and university students in Gaza receive the required certificates from it, noting that 3,714 lessons have been provided, and 500 exams have been conducted, including 7,522 questions. Al Jazeera Net reviewed several opinions from school students in the Gaza Strip who have been following their lessons through this application for weeks, where Tulin Al-Turkmani confirmed that she was unable to understand the study materials before obtaining the application. She added that after listening to and watching the educational lessons through the comprehensive explanations from the teachers, she was able to take the exam and achieve full marks in many subjects after regularly following the lessons. Official statistics from the Palestinian Ministry of Education showed that the ongoing Israeli aggression for more than a year has deprived 650,000 male and female students of their right to education, in addition to the martyrdom of 11,600 children of school age, 750 teachers and educators, 1,100 higher education students, and 130 scholars and university professors. Additionally, 39,000 students were prevented from taking the general secondary exam at the end of the last academic year, and 58,000 children were deprived of the joy of joining the first grade at the beginning of the new year, while 90 schools and universities in Gaza suffered complete destruction or severe damage, according to the ministry."}
